      <header>&amp;RScoring Clarifications&amp;n</header>
      <slot>6</slot>
      <level>210</level>
      <author>270853</author>
      <date>1054098086</date>
      <authorname>Tzeentch</authorname>
      <text>
Realism:
This is pretty straightforward. A contestant who does things that are not
physically possible, even with a trampoline, stunt doubles and a crack film
editor, will score low. A person whose emotes seem very feasible will score
high.

Clarity:
This is how easy it is for the reader (i.e. the judge) to understand the
emote. If the judge ends up having no idea what the emoter is attempting to
do, that emoter will score low. If the judge can read through the emotes
quickly and get a good picture of what is going on in one pass, the emoter
will score high.

Strategy:
This is the ability to actually win a fight while staying within the boundary of
realism. Working your opponent into positions where they cannot avoid your hits
and coming up with non-superman ways to avoid taking hits of your own are the
best ways to score high. Doing unrealistic things in order to score hits or
avoid taking them will just detract from the realism score, not boost the
strategy score.

Style:
Note that this is not called &quot;flair.&quot; It is, however, a hard category to
quantify. A consistant voice that makes it easy to identify the emoter is one
thing that will be looked for. Not quirks or ticks, but a distinctive voice
and combat style. This is also the catch-all category for things such as
whether or not the spar flows as RP (yes, a tournament spar is still RP), is
interesting, whether the combatants stay in character, etc. The whole is often
greater than the sum of the parts. This category is a way for the judges to
score on the whole.

And that's it. Direct any questions to me through tells or mudmail. As I
composed this while posting it, I'm sure I typo'd something or left something
unexplained that was obvious to myself but not to those outside my little
corner of insanity.

-Tze
</text>
